<div class="post-date">Jan 10</div>
<h2><a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?id=1038" title="The Ohio is out and about"> The Ohio is out and about</a></h2>

<div class="entry">


     

  	<p><img alt="Ohioflooded.jpg" src="http://www.ontheriversedge.com/images/Ohioflooded.jpg" width="500" height="375" border="0" /></p>

	<p>The river is now definitely out of its banks, fortunately we&#8217;re only looking at minor flooding here. While it&#8217;s covered our riverfront road and parklands, I&#8217;m hoping it stays out of the few houses that are down on the river front. They suffered enough in 1997.</p>

	<p>I posted a <a href="http://homepage.mac.com/egyarnetsky/PhotoAlbum5.html">new album of photos</a> Darlene and I took yesterday and today. When you check out the photos, take a look at the riverfront light posts. When the flood waters of 1997 crested, only the globe on top was above the water.</p>

	<p>For those who know Madison, the photo above is taken at dusk looking west from the <a href="http://www.mapquest.com/maps/map.adp?country=US&#38;addtohistory=&#38;formtype=address&#38;searchtype=address&#38;cat=&#38;address=Elm%20St%20%26%20W%20Vaughn%20Dr&#38;city=Madison&#38;state=IN&#38;zipcode=47250&#38;searchtab=home">foot of Elm Street</a> (three blocks south of our library). The walled area is the lower lawn of the Lanier Mansion.</p>

	<p>The river&#8217;s expected to crest tomorrow late morning. We&#8217;ll be out taking more photos. It&#8217;s odd to be gawkers. I guess it&#8217;s the old journalistic instincts to go out and cover the story.</p>

	<p>For &#8220;real&#8221; daily coverage, however, check the <a href="www.madisoncourier.com">The Madison Courier</a>.</p>



 
<div class="line"></div>

<div class="smallcat">Posted in <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?c=Madison">Madison</a></div>
<div class="smalluser"> by <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?author=E.G.+Yarnetsky">E.G. Yarnetsky</a></div>
