<div class="post-date">Jan  8</div>
<h2><a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?id=1036" title="Waters are a coming?"> Waters are a coming?</a></h2>

<div class="entry">


     

  	<p>Well, I guess the Midwest can&#8217;t get a snow storm and then days of rain without the Ohio River sending it all back our way.</p>

	<p>The National Weather Service&#8217;s <a href="http://www.crh.noaa.gov/cgi-bin/ahps.cgi?LMK&#38;clfi3">Advanced Hydrologic Prediction Service</a> is saying the Ohio River will likely top flood stage here in Madison Sunday morning. Here&#8217;s the graph&#8230;</p>

	<p><img alt="clfi3.gif" src="http://www.ontheriversedge.com/images/clfi3.gif" width="450" height="350" border="0" /></p>

	<p>I covered the last flood in 1997 extensively for <a href="http://www.madisoncourier.com">The Madison Courier</a>. I&#8217;m hoping there won&#8217;t be a repeat. Houses along Vaughn Drive (our river road) were flooded halfway up the first floor. The river hit 460.90 feet, the eighth worst recorded flood at Madison.</p>

	<p>It was amazingly scary to look inside the homes after being visited by the Ohio River. A half foot of river silt covered every surface from the floor to the sinks. The walls were laid bare half-way to the ceiling, the drywall disintegrated. We are so used to seeing the barriers, suddenly seeing straight through a house with only beams in the way is like looking at a ghost.</p>

	<p><b>Note</b>: The river crests are measured from sea level, not the bottom of the river. For comparison, the river bottom at Madison is at 403.2 or 402.3 (I can never remember which). It&#8217;s normal depth at this time of year would probably be about 420. I added the river stage under Madison links.</p>



 
<div class="line"></div>

<div class="smallcat">Posted in <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?c=Madison">Madison</a></div>
<div class="smalluser"> by <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?author=E.G.+Yarnetsky">E.G. Yarnetsky</a></div>
