<div class="post-date">Dec 26</div>
<h2><a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?id=1026" title="Our snow from Darlene&#8217;s perspective"> Our snow from Darlene&#8217;s perspective</a></h2>

<div class="entry">


     

  	<p><b>Editor&#8217;s note</b>: <i>This is an edited version of what Darlene wrote my mom. It stated our situation so perfectly that I got her permission to post it here. Here&#8217;s Darlene&#8230;</i></p>

	<p>Imagine our downtown where many of the residents do not have off street parking.  Now imagine 17 inches of snow dumped on that town in less than 48 hours&#8230;</p>

	<p>Jer and I returned this afternoon and I parked the van in the space we dug it out of.  As soon as I pulled all the way in, it occurred to me that getting back out could be a challenge.  Said parking space is still snow covered, a bit slippery, and the nose of the van is downhill a bit from the rear of the van.</p>

	<p>Out of sheer stubborness I decided I was going to try to get van out myself and pick Jerry up at 5.  Felt I should have practice in doing this sort of thing as you never know when you might need the skills.  Proceeded outside.</p>

	<p>Cardboard under wheels- no luck.  Moving van back and forth, no luck.  (only proceeded in moving to the far right side of the parking space) Hopped out of car to reposition cardboard.  Landed in 3 foot drift, slid out of drift to bounce on my kneecaps on the street. (3 points for humoring any onlookers at gas station). Repositioned cardboard, trudged back through snowdrift and tried again.  It is about 22 degrees outside and 2 kind boys on bikes volunteered to push. They were not very large, but quite insistent.  (a bit bored I suspect) No luck.  Man pulls up in truck, attaches chain to van and with boys pushing on other end I am freed!</p>

	<p>Slowly make my way across slush covered streets to library where I happily drop the problem in Jerry&#8217;s lap.  Ok hon, if we park in our space, we may not be able to get back out again.  Other spaces either have 4 foot drifts in them or cars covered in four foot drifts in them.  City lots are still snow covered.</p>

	<p>Head to nearest city parking lot.  Maybe it was more usable than it appeared.  Just before pulling in ran into friend Ellen who had just her own car freed from the snow.  Jerry proceeds cautiously into lot not realizing where Ellen had just been freed from!  Immediately get stuck in same mess that Ellen had just been pulled from in said parking lot.  Ellen&#8217;s husband and father in law and another friendly bystander along with Jerry proceed to push us out of drift and some kind (and probably exasperated) soul with a front loader plows a path to allow us to get out of the lot.</p>

	<p>So with no other parking opportunities, we were forced back to our same sloping parking space that we dug ourselves out of Thursday and will probably have to be pushed out of Tuesday afternoon.</p>

	<p>This is how we are managing the snow here in Madison. ( I am really glad we are not in Texas or Louisiana!)  I can&#8217;t wait to see what happens when businesses and the courthouse, city hall etc. reopen tomorrow.</p>

	<p>I asked for snow and so far I am still amused by it.</p>



 
<div class="line"></div>

<div class="smallcat">Posted in <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?c=Madison">Madison</a></div>
